e>Bassel</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE002544%2F1"><gtr:id>E784FCCA-0F88-4CFF-A913-312573E07E30</gtr:id><gtr:title>From Refugee Woman to Citizen: The Politics of Integration in France and Canada</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E002544/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This research examines the gaps between refugee women?s experiences and the claims made as to the ways in which refugee women?s legal, political and social/welfare needs are met. Canadian multiculturalism and French republican assimilation are compared in the context of the experiences of Somali women. Data collection involved interviews with members of the Somali communities, Non Governmental Organisations and government representatives, and participant observation. Recent debates focus on whether cultural group rights clash with gender equality, giving powerful men political support to impose ?traditions? on women, who are often particularly vulnerable group members. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The comparison between Canada and France was developed in order to use empirical evidence to test the causal claims made about the impact of models and policies on women. This comparison of contrasting contexts (multiculturalism in Canada, republican assimilation in France) provides insight into what role these models are in fact playing at the level of practice and experience, and which causal claims (if any) are valid.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>Findings from the research demonstrate the interconnection within refugee women?s experiences of barriers of poverty, racism, gender discrimination and vulnerability in asylum procedures. In contrast to current debates over balancing culture and women?s rights, it is necessary to support and enable refugee women?s meaningful political participation in making claims in the public sphere based on their own definition of their needs in order to address interconnected barriers.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2007-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-02-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>35550</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>65746F1F-B825-4C2E-8C92-59E3C5594273</gtr:id><gtr:title>Citizenship as Interpellation: Refugee Women and the State</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Government and Opposition</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/e170e58f3fffc0e5310e1af9afd5261a"><gtr:id>e170e58f3fffc0e5310e1af9afd5261a</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Bassel L</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2008-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>doi_53cfa4fa4e07c442</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>4C882E66-0274-4FD7-B5A0-9FAA731FD9D0</gtr:id><gtr:title>Intersectional Politics at the Boundaries of the Nation State</gtr: